{"parse":{"title":"star","pageid":1571,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"star\"}}\n==English==\n[[Image:Merope.jpg|thumb|right|'''Stars''' (1, 2).]]\n[[Image:Pentagram (fixed width).svg|thumb|right|A '''star''' shape (3).|class=skin-invert-image]]\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|en|:inh|enm:sterre|tree=1}}\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₂eHs-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|sterre}}, from {{inh|en|ang|steorra||star}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*sterrō}}, variant of {{m|gmw-pro|*sternō}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*sternô}}, {{m|gem-pro|*sternǭ||star}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₂stḗr||star}}. {{doublet|en|aster}}; related to {{m|en|estoile}}, {{m|en|étoile}}, {{m|en|stella}}, and {{m|en|stelo}}.\n\n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|sco|starn}}, {{m|sco|ster|t=star}}, {{cog|yol|starr}}, {{m|yol|steor|t=star}}, {{cog|stq|Stiern|t=star}}, {{cog|fy|stjer|t=star}}, {{cog|cim|stèrn|t=star}}, {{cog|nl|ster|t=star}}, {{cog|de|Stern|t=star}}, {{cog|lb|Stär|t=star}}, {{cog|mhn|stern|t=star}}, {{cog|wym|śtaom|t=star}}, {{cog|yi|שטערן|t=star}}, {{cog|da,nb|stjerne|t=star}}, {{cog|fo|stjørna|t=star}}, {{cog|gmq-gut|stjännå|t=star}}, {{cog|is|stjarna|t=star}}, {{cog|nn|skjødna}}, {{m|nn|stjerne|t=star}}, {{cog|sv|stjärna|t=star}}, {{cog|gme-cgo|stein|t=star}}, {{cog|got|𐍃𐍄𐌰𐌹𐍂𐌽𐍉|t=star}}, {{cog|fr|étoile|t=star}}, {{cog|ist|stila|t=star}}, {{cog|ruo|ste|t=star}}, {{cog|it|stella|t=star}}, {{cog|ruq|steau̯ă|t=star}}, {{cog|mwl|streilha|t=star}}, {{cog|oc|estela|t=star}}, {{cog|pt|estrela|t=star}}, {{cog|rm|staila|t=star}}, {{cog|ro|stea|t=star}}, {{cog|sc|isteddu|t=star}}, {{cog|scn|stidda|t=star}}, {{cog|es|estrella|t=star}}, {{cog|vec|stéła|t=star}}, {{cog|wa|sitoele|t=star}}, {{cog|la|stēlla|t=star}}, {{cog|grc|ἀστήρ|t=star}}, {{cog|el|αστέρι|t=star}}, {{cog|xcl|աստղ||sc=Armn|t=star}}, {{cog|fa|ستاره|tr=setâre|t=star}}, {{cog|tg|ситора|t=star}}, {{cog|ps|ستوری|tr=storay|t=star}}, {{cog|mzn|اساره|tr=ëssâre|t=star}}, {{cog|kmr|stêr|t=star}}, {{cog|ckb|ئەستێرە|t=star}}, {{cog|zza|astare|t=star}}, {{cog|os|стъалы|t=star}}, {{cog|hi|तारा|t=star}}, {{cog|ur|تارا|tr=tārā|t=star}}, {{cog|pa|ਤਾਰਾ|t=star}}, {{cog|gu|તારો|t=star}}, {{cog|sa|तारा|t=star}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/stɑː(ɹ)/|a=UK}}\n** {{audio|en|En-uk-star.ogg|a=London}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Back ache-star.wav|a=London}}\n* {{enPR|stär|a=US}}, {{IPA|en|/stɑɹ/}}\n** {{audio|en|en-us-star.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{IPA|en|/staː(ɹ)/|a=AU}}\n* {{rhymes|en|ɑː(ɹ)|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# Any small, natural and [[bright]] dot in the sky, most visible in the night or [[twilight]] sky. ''This sense includes the [[planet]]s, but it is now sometimes used in exclusion of them due to influence from the technical astronomical sense.''\n#: {{ux|en| He loved watching the '''stars''' in the sky with her.}}\n## {{lb|en|astrology|typically in the plural}} A [[planet]] thought to [[influence]] one's [[fate]]; (''figuratively'') fate or luck.\n##: {{ux|en|What's in the '''stars''' for you today? Find out in our horoscope.}}\n##: {{ux|en|star-crossed ''(meaning 'ill-fated')''}}\n##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 6-1|act=IV|scene=v|page=112|column=2|passage=But O malignant and ill-boading '''Starres''',{{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:Scott Ivanhoe\n|passage=Men bless their '''stars''' and call it luxury.}}\n##* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=V|pages=69–70|pageref=70|passage=But Miss Thorn relieved the situation by laughing aloud,{{...}}. By the time we reached the house we were thanking our '''stars''' she had come.}}\n# {{senseid|en|Q523}}{{lb|en|star}} A very massive ball of [[plasma]] with strong enough gravity to have ongoing fusion of [[hydrogen]] or heavier elements in its core. ''In strict technical usage, the [[Sun]] is included.''\n# ''senses derived from the apparent shape of a star in the sky when blurred by the eyes to have streaks''\n## A shape made of a few streaks meeting at a shared midpoint.\n### {{lb|en|printing}} An [[asterisk]] ([[*]]) or comparable [[symbol]] (e.g., ★, ☆, ✶, ✦, ✧, ✷, ✪, ⭐) inspired by a [[celestial]] star.\n###* {{quote-journal|en|year=1960|month=December|title=The Glasgow Suburban Electrification is opened|journal=Trains Illustrated|page=714|text=Above all, the 48-page timetables of the new service, which have been distributed free at every station in the scheme, are a model to the rest of B.R. For the first time on British Railways, so far as we are aware, a substantial timetable has been produced, not only without a single footnote but also devoid of all wearisome asterisks, '''stars''', letter suffixes and other hieroglyphics.}}\n### {{lb|en|networking|figurative in origin}} A [[network topology]] with multiple computers individually merging to one central [[switch]], thus free of risk of [[collision|collisions]]. A [[single point of failure]] can occur if the switch experiences [[corruption]].\n### A simple dance, or part of a dance, where a group of four dancers each put their right or left hand in the middle and turn around in a circle. You call them right-hand stars or left-hand stars, depending on the hand which is in the middle.\n## {{lb|en|shapes|geometry}} A concave [[polygon]] with regular, pointy protrusions and indentations, usually with four, five, or six points.\n### A star-shaped [[ornament]] worn on the breast to indicate rank or honour in a military. ''Now often used metonymically for military rankings.''\n###* {{RQ:Tennyson Maud|stanza=8|page=132|passage={{...}}on whom {{...}} / Lavish Honour shower’d all her '''stars''',{{...}}}}\n###: {{ux|en|[[three-star general]]}}\n### A [[symbol]] used to rate [[hotel]]s, [[film]]s, etc. with a higher number of stars denoting better quality.\n###* {{quote-journal|en-US|author=w:Kelefa Sanneh|title=How Music Criticism Lost Its Edge|work=The New Yorker|date=2025-08-25|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2025/09/01/how-music-criticism-lost-its-edge|issn=0028-792X|passage=And the first music review I remember reading was in ''Rolling Stone'', which rated albums on a scale of one to five '''stars''', or so I thought. In 1990, the début solo album by Andrew Ridgeley, who had sung alongside George Michael in the pop duo Wham!, was awarded only half a '''star'''.}}\n# ''senses relating to fame''\n## {{lb|en|acting}} An [[actor]] in a [[lead]]ing [[role]].\n##: {{ux|en|Many Hollywood '''stars''' attended the launch party.}}\n## An exceptionally [[talent]]ed or [[famous]] person, often in a specific field; a [[celebrity]].\n##: {{ux|en|His teacher tells us he is a '''star''' pupil.}}\n##: {{ux|en|I met my favourite '''star''' at the public event.}}\n##* {{quote-text|en|year=1862|author=Mary Elizabeth Braddon|title=Lady Audley's Secret\n|passage=The king who had worn her colours was dead and gone; the court of which she had been a '''star''' had passed away; powerful functionaries and great magistrates, who might perhaps have helped her, were mouldering in their graves; {{...}}}}\n##* {{RQ:Rinehart Hopwood Bat|chapter=The Shadow of the Bat|page=8|passage='''Star''' reporter, leg-man, cub, veteran gray in the trade—one and all they tried to pin the Bat like a caught butterfly to the front page of their respective journals—soon or late each gave up, beaten. He was news—{{...}}—the brief, staccato recital of his career in the morgues of the great dailies grew longer and more incredible each day.}}\n##* {{quote-journal|en|journal=w:Architectural Digest|date=May 2026|volume=83|issue=4|title=Feeling Zen|author=Sam Cochran|page=100\n|text=Known for an unerring attention to detail, poetic use of materials, and intuitive sensitivity to scale, Thulstrup has long been a '''star''' in his native Denmark.}}\n## {{lb|en|figurative}} (Someone's) [[success]] or [[fame]].\n##: {{coa|en|someone's '''star''' is rising / has risen}}\n##* {{RQ:Snowden Permanent Record|text=It’s only in hindsight that I’m able to appreciate just how high my '''star''' had risen. I’d gone from being the student who couldn’t speak in class to being the teacher of the language of a new age, from the child of modest, middle-class Beltway parents to the man living the island life and making so much money that it had lost its meaning.}}\n# {{lb|en|Jamaica|MLE|AAVE|by extension}} A [[friend]], a [[mate]], a [[pal]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2003|author=Michael Maynard|title=Games Men Play|page=127|passage=\"Wha'ppen, '''star'''!\" Hector said, grinning to reveal a gold-capped tooth. He told everyone it was solid twenty-four carat, but if it was, he would have wrenched it out with pliers to pawn to the highest bidder by now.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|year=2003|artist=w:Goldie Looking Chain|album=The Manifesto|title=Soap Bar|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EtVZbQkvk_Q|passage=Hello claat, what you doing '''spar'''?{{...}}It's got three ring tones, that's the name for the ring. There's this one, right (''ring tone sounds''). That's fucking safe, '''spar'''. But mostly, I bought it for this, check this one out, claat!}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2017|author=Les Back|title=New Ethnicities and Urban Culture: Racisms and Multiculture in Young Lives|url=https://www.google.co.uk/books/edition/New_Ethnicities_And_Urban_Culture/i48ZDgAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Whappen+star&pg=PT154&printsec=frontcover|passage=Switches character to the street-wise Ragamuffin, speaking out of the corner of his mouth in Creole: \"Whappen now '''star'''! Seckle, seckle now people! Cool, cool na baass! [what is happening friends? Settle down]}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2022|author=Moses McKenzie|title=An Olive Grove in Ends|url=https://www.google.co.uk/books/edition/An_Olive_Grove_in_Ends/zv1FEAAAQBAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=Wagwan+star&pg=PT231&printsec=frontcover|passage='Dey ain't mine,' Stacey snapped, flicking her head towards the yutes in the bedroom. 'I'm juss lookin after dem fi mi fren dem. I only av six pickney by tree men enuh, '''star'''.'}}\n# A composition of [[combustible]] matter used in the heading of rockets, in mines, etc., which, exploding in the air, presents a starlike appearance.\n\n====Usage notes====\n* In traditional use, the planets are stars but the sun is not; in astronomy, the sun is a star but the planets are not (and the Earth is counted among the planets).\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|en|aster}} {{q|obsolete}}\n* {{sense|astronomy}} {{l|mul|✶}} or {{l|en|＊}} {{qualifier|abbreviation}}, {{l|en|sun}}\n\n====Hypernyms====\n* {{sense|astronomy}} {{l|en|celestial body}}\n\n====Hyponyms====\n{{col4|en\n|Ae star\n|barium star\n|Be star\n|binary star\n|blue hook star\n|boson star\n|carbon star\n|clock star\n|compact star\n|dark star\n|death star\n|double star\n|dwarf star\n|early-type star\n|exotic star\n|faxed star\n|fixed star\n|flare star\n|frozen star\n|giant star\n|guide star\n|helium star\n|infant star\n|low mass star\n|multiple star\n|neutron star\n|north star\n|orphan star\n|Planck star\n|polar star,pole star\n|proto-neutron star,protoneutron star\n|protostar\n|quadruple star\n|quark star\n|red giant\n|reference star\n|royal star\n|shell star\n|shooting star\n|single star\n|superstar\n|symbiotic star\n|T Tauri star\n|telescopic star\n|trinary star\n|triple star\n|white dwarf\n|Wolf-Rayet star\n}}\n\n{{col4|en\n|Barnard's Star\n|Dog Star\n|Garnet Star\n|North Star}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n{{col|en|starboard|Starcross|starline|starrify|starwatcher\n|5-star\n|action star\n|adult star\n|aim for the stars|stars o' mine\n|all-star\n|amylum star|aniseed star|biscuit star|comet star|cushion star|Siemens star\n|angstrom star\n|antistar\n|Argead star\n|astar\n|A star|strangeon star\n|back-cloth star\n|barnstar\n|barn star,barn-star\n|bar star\n|basket star\n|bat star\n|bearded star\n|Besselian star number\n|bestar\n|binary star\n|bistar\n|black hole star\n|blazingstar,blazing star\n|blitzar\n|bluestar,blue star\n|bog star|star of anise|star section\n|bold star\n|bright and morning star\n|brittle star\n|Bronze Star\n|Brunswick star\n|Burmese star tortoise\n|chemically peculiar star\n|Christmas Star,Christmas star\n|collapsar\n|co-star\n|costar\n|count one's lucky stars\n|day star\n|daystar\n|double star\n|Druze star\n|dwarf star\n|earthstar\n|enstar\n|Eurostar\n|evening star\n|evenstar\n|falling star\n|faxed-star\n|feather star\n|field star\n|film star\n|five-star\n|forest star\n|gender star\n|Georgian star\n|gold star\n|Gold Star\n|gold star family\n|gold star father\n|gold star gay\n|gold star lesbian\n|gold star mother\n|gold star parent\n|gold star wife\n|gravastar\n|guest-star\n|guest star\n|guiding star\n|hitch one's wagon to a star\n|Hodge star\n|Hubble's Star\n|Indian star tortoise\n|instar\n|in the stars\n|Kleene star\n|late-type star\n|lodestar\n|lone star tick\n|lucky star\n|main-sequence star\n|megastar\n|Mexican star\n|Michelin star\n|Mittag-Leffler star\n|Moravian star\n|morning star\n|movie star\n|multiple star\n|multistarrer\n|my stars\n|nanostar\n|neutron star\n|ninja star\n|nonstar\n|oh my stars\n|one-star\n|O star\n|pole-star\n|pop star\n|porn star\n|porn-star martini\n|porn-star name\n|prairie star\n|promise the stars\n|Provo all-star\n|pseudostar\n|pulsar\n|quasi-star\n|quasistar\n|quintuple star system\n|radio star\n|reach for the stars\n|Red Star\n|rising star\n|rockstar\n|rock star\n|rosy feather star\n|runaway star\n|sand star\n|sea-star\n|sea star\n|seastar\n|see stars\n|semistar\n|serpent star\n|smallflower woodland star\n|soapstar\n|Sputnik star\n|standard star\n|star 69\n|star-69\n|star activity\n|star anise\n|star aniseed\n|star apple\n|star attraction\n|Starbase\n|starbase\n|star base\n|starbath\n|starbathe\n|starbeam\n|star begonia\n|star billing\n|starbirth\n|starboard#Etymology 2\n|starbound\n|starboy\n|starburst\n|star cactus\n|starcast\n|star chamber\n|star chart\n|starchitect\n|starchitecture\n|star-city\n|Star City\n|star city\n|star clock\n|star cloud\n|star cluster\n|star-cover\n|starcraft\n|star crossed\n|star-crossed\n|starcruiser\n|star cucumber\n|stardate\n|stardock\n|stardom\n|stardrift\n|star-drive\n|star drive\n|stardrive\n|star duckweed\n|stardust\n|stareater\n|star factory\n|starfall\n|starfaring\n|starfield\n|starfighter\n|starfilled\n|star finch\n|starfish\n|star fleet\n|starflower\n|star-forming\n|star fort\n|star frame\n|starfrontlet\n|star fruit\n|starfruit\n|starfuck\n|starfucker\n|star-fucker\n|starfucking\n|starful\n|stargate\n|Stargateverse\n|star gauge\n|stargaze\n|stargazer\n|star grass\n|star height\n|starhood\n|star hyacinth\n|star in the east\n|Star Island\n|star it\n|star jasmine\n|star jelly\n|star jump\n|starless\n|starlet\n|star lifting\n|starlight\n|starlighted\n|starlike\n|starliner\n|starlit\n|starlitten\n|star lizard\n|starlore\n|starly\n|star macromolecule\n|star magnolia\n|starmaker\n|star-maker\n|starmaking\n|starman\n|star mangrove\n|star-map\n|starmatter\n|star meat\n|starmonger\n|starnose\n|star-nosed mole\n|star note\n|Star of Bethlehem\n|star-of-Bethlehem\n|Star of David\n|star-of-the-earth\n|Star of the Sea\n|star of Vergina\n|star packer\n|star pagoda\n|star pass\n|star picket\n|star pine\n|star plate\n|star plot\n|star polygon\n|star polyhedron\n|star polymer\n|starport\n|star prisoner\n|star prize\n|star projector\n|starproof\n|starquake\n|star quality\n|star quartz\n|star-reed\n|starrer\n|star ring\n|starrise\n|starrish\n|star rot\n|star route\n|star ruby\n|starry\n|starry-eyed\n|stars align\n|star sapphire\n|stars are aligned\n|starscape\n|star schema\n|Star Scout\n|star sedge\n|star seed\n|starset\n|starshade\n|star shell\n|starshine\n|starship\n|star shot\n|star-shower\n|star shower\n|star sign\n|stars in one's eyes\n|star-sixty-nine\n|star sixty-nine\n|starsnout\n|starspot\n|starstone\n|star stream\n|star-strewn\n|star-struck\n|star-studded\n|starstuff\n|star system\n|star the glaze\n|starthistle\n|star-thistle\n|star thistle\n|starthroat\n|star topology\n|startracker\n|star tracker\n|star trail\n|Star Trek\n|star-triangle relation\n|star turn\n|star up\n|star vault\n|star vehicle\n|star-vehicle\n|star vessel\n|star violet\n|starviolet\n|star visitor\n|starward\n|starwards\n|Star Wars\n|starweed\n|starwheel\n|star wheel\n|starwise\n|star witness\n|star word\n|starwort\n|strange quark star\n|strange star\n|substar\n|sunflower sea star\n|sunflower star\n|sun star\n|superstar\n|technetium star\n|television star\n|thank one's lucky stars\n|thank one's stars\n|three-star\n|three stars\n|throwing star\n|track star\n|tristar\n|under a lucky star\n|under the stars\n|unstar\n|variable star\n|venous star\n|Vergina star\n|very low mass star\n|wandering star,wanderstar\n|wish upon a star\n|Wolfstar\n|woodland star\n|worm-star\n|WTF Star\n|yellow star\n|zombie star\n}}\n\n====Related terms====\n* {{l|en|estoile}}\n* {{l|en|étoile}}\n* {{l|en|stella}}\n* {{l|en|stellar}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desctree|srn|stari}}\n* {{desc|fi|stara|id=star|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|fr|star|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|de|Star|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|hu|sztár|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|it|star|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sw|staa|bor=1}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{see translation subpage|Noun}}\n\n====See also====\n* [[Thesaurus:star]]\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[appear]] as a featured performer or headliner, especially in an entertainment program.\n#: {{ux|en|She '''starred''' in dozens of silent movies.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1902|author=Robert Marshall Grade|title=The Haunted Major\n|passage=I was inundated with invitations; {{...}} I felt, indeed, much as a great actor must when he goes ''''starring'''' in the provinces.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[feature]] (a performer or a headliner), especially in a movie or an entertainment program.\n#: {{ux|en|The show '''stars''' Calista Flockhart as a high-powered lawyer.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2004|author=David W. Menefee|title=The First Female Stars: Women of the Silent Era|page=4|passage=\"What followed this decision was exactly what we had expected: Mr. Fox, realizing that the public was tiring of Theda Bara in vampire roles, announced that he would '''star''' her in a production of Romeo and Juliet,\" she illustrated.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To mark with a star or [[asterisk]].\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To set or adorn with stars, or bright, radiating bodies; to [[bespangle]].\n#* {{RQ:Young Night-Thoughts|314|Thy gloomy Grandeurs (''Nature''’s moſt auguſt, / Inſpiring Aſpect!) claim a grateful Verſe; / And, like a ſable Curtain '''ſtarr’d''' with Gold, / Drawn o’er my Labours paſt, ſhall cloſe the Scene.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To [[shine]] like a star.\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|to mark with an asterisk}} {{l|en|asterisk}}\n\n====Translations====\n{{trans-top|to appear as a featured performer or headliner}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|играя главна роля}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|protagonitzar}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|ĉefroli}}\n* Estonian: {{t+|et|täht|s}}, {{t+|et|staar|s}}, {{t|et|peategelane|s}}, {{t|et|peaesineja|s}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[esittää]] [[pääosaa]]}}, {{t+|fi|tähdittää}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|protagoniser}}, {{t|fr|[[tenir]] [[le]] [[rôle]] [[principal]]}}\n* German: {{t|de|[[die]] [[Hauptrolle]] [[spielen]]|lit=play the lead}} {{qualifier|film}}\n* Hungarian: {{t|hu|[[főszereplő|főszereplőként]] [[szerepel]]}}, {{t|hu|[[főszerep]]et/[[sztárszerep]]et [[játszik]]}}\n* Interlingua: {{t-check|ia|[[tener]] [[le]] [[rolo]] [[principal]]}}\n* Italian: {{t|it|[[avere]] [[il]] [[ruolo]] [[principale]]}}, {{t|it|[[avere]] [[il]] [[ruolo]] [[da]] [[protagonista]]}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|主演|alt=主演する|tr=[[しゅえん]]する, shuen suru}}\n* Ohlone:\n*: Northern Ohlone: {{t|cst|'ósé}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|protagonizar}}, {{t+|pt|estrelar}} {{qualifier|Brazil}}\n* Spanish: {{t|es|estelarizar}}, {{t+|es|protagonizar}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|[[முன்னணியில்]] [[நடி]]|lit=''act in the leading role(s)''}}\n* Telugu: {{t+|te|నక్షత్రం}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|serennu}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to feature (a performer or a headliner), especially in a movie or an entertainment program}}\n* Hungarian: {{t|hu|[[főszereplő|főszereplőként]] [[szerepeltet]]}}, {{t|hu|[[főszereplő]]je|lit=…’s protagonist is}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to mark with a star or asterisk}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|tähistama|s}}, {{t|et|tärnima|s}}, {{t|et|tähtima|s}}, {{t|et|märkima|s}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|megcsillagoz}}, {{t|hu|[[csillag]]gal [[megjelöl]]}}\n* Tamil: {{t|ta|[[உடுக்குறி]] [[இடு]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to set or adorn with stars, or bright, radiating bodies; to bespangle}}\n* Hungarian: {{t|hu|[[csillag]]gal [[díszít]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|to shine like a star\n|shine}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{l|en|astronomy}}\n* {{l|en|black hole}}\n* {{l|en|galaxy}}\n* {{l|en|moon}}\n* {{l|en|mullet}}<!-- a type of star in heraldry -->\n* {{l|en|planet}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{pedia|star}}\n* {{pedia|star (disambiguation)}}\n* {{R:wquote|en|stars}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=arst|tars|sart|ARTS|arts.|'rats|tsar|tars-|ARTs|rats|Sart|srat|Srta.|RATs|RAST|Arts|stra.|Srta|arts|astr-|TSRA|RTAs|TRAs}}\n\n{{cln|en|endearing terms|terms of address}}\n{{C|en|Celestial bodies|Light sources|Nuclear fusion|Dances|People|Polygons|Shapes}}\n\n==Dutch==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|nl|dum|star}}, from {{inh|nl|odt|*star}}, from {{inh|nl|gmw-pro|*star}}, from {{inh|nl|gem-pro|*staraz}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|nl|/stɑr/}}\n* {{audio|nl|Nl-star.ogg}}\n* {{hyphenation|nl|star}}\n* {{rhymes|nl|ɑr|s=1}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{nl-adj}}\n\n# [[stiff]], [[frozen]]\n# [[rigid]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{nl-decl-adj|starre}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|nl|halsstarrig}}\n* {{l|nl|starheid}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:nl:Woordenlijst}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|fr|:bor|en:star}}\n{{bor+|fr|en|star}}. {{doublet|fr|aster}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|Fr-star.ogg}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fr-noun|f}}\n\n# {{l|en|star}} {{gl|celebrity}}\n#: {{uxi|fr|Elle est devenue '''star'''.|She's become a '''star'''.}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|fr|stariser}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|fr|arts}}, {{l|fr|rats}}, {{l|fr|tsar}}\n\n==Interlingua==\n\n===Verb===\n{{ia-verb|ar}}\n# to {{l|en|stand}}\n# to be {{l|en|do}}ing (well, poorly, okay); to {{l|en|fare}}; to {{l|en|feel}}; to {{l|en|be}} in a certain state\n#:{{ux|ia|Como '''sta''' tu?|How '''are''' you '''doing'''?}}\n#:{{ux|ia|Io '''sta''' ben, gratias, e tu?|I'm '''doing''' well, thanks. How about you?}}\n\n====Usage notes====\nThis is not typically used for location.\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{etymon|it|:bor|en:star}}\n{{bor+|it|en|star}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{it-pr|stàr}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{it-noun|f|#}}\n\n# {{l|en|star}} {{gloss|celebrity}}\n#: {{syn|it|celebrità|divo}}\n#: {{coi|it|'''star''' del cinema|movie '''star'''}}\n# {{lb|it|maths}} [[asterisk]], {{ng|pronunciation of {{m|mul|*}} symbol}}\n#: {{par|it|asterisco}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|it|a=arst|stra-|tras-}}\n\n==Jamaican Creole==\n\n===Noun===\n{{jam-noun}}\n\n# A [[friend]], a [[mate]], a [[pal]]\n#* {{quote-song|jam|date=2008-08-26|artist=w:Vybz Kartel|album=Most Wanted|track=9|title=Kill Dem|url=https://genius.com/Vybz-kartel-kill-dem-lyrics|passage=Me full ah gun pon di Gaza. Run some boy file and find out dem a barber. Jah know '''star''', what dem ah try?|translation=I empty a gun on the Gaza. I run some boy's file and find out they're a barber. God knows '''mate''', what are they trying to do?}}\n#* {{quote-song|jam|year=2009|artist=w:Vybz Kartel|title=Whe Dem A Go Run Go|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7SWHC2_S17s|note=01:58-02:01|passage=Whe dem a go run go, Whe dem a go run go '''star'''? Start way dem caan run go far.|translation=Where are they going to, where are they going to run to '''friend'''? They start to go away but they can’t get far (before getting shot).}}\n\n==Maltese==\n{{mt-root|s-t-r}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|mt|stara}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{ety|mt|:inh|ar:سِتَار|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|mt|/staːr/}}\n* {{rhymes|mt|aːr|s=1}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{mt-noun|g=m|p=stari}}\n\n# [[veil]]\n#: {{syn|mt|velu|q=commoner}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|enm|sterre}}\n\n==Mirandese==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|mwl|la|sto|stāre}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{mwl-pr}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{mwl-verb}}\n\n# to [[be]] {{gloss|indicates a temporary state}}\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{mwl-conj}}\n\n====See also====\n{{col|mwl|ser<t:to be><qq:indicates a permanent quality>}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:mwl:PVMP|493}}\n\n==Northern Kurdish==\n\n===Etymology===\nAkin to {{cog|ckb|ستار|t=retire, retreat, take refuge}}, originally a descendant of {{inh|kmr|ine-pro|*steh₂-}} but now conflated with {{cog|ar|سِتَار}}, hence the second sense. Proposed to be the name of an ancient deity by some based on the common expression ''\"Ya Star!\"'' (\"O Star!\", said to ask God for endurance and strength).\n\n===Noun===\n{{kmr-noun|f}}\n\n# [[standing]], the ability to stand or stay at one's place, strength, energy; not worrying or being bored, calmness.\n# [[protection]], [[coverage]]\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{sense|the ability to stand, strength of legs, energy}} {{l|kmr|qidûm}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* [[star kirin]] (\"to protect\")\n* [[star lê hatin]] (\"to find the strength to, to find the courage to\")\n* [[stargeh]] (\"refuge\")\n* [[sitirîn]] (\"to calm down, to mellow down, to stay put\")\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n{{wp|nn:+e}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nn-noun-m1}}\n\n# alternative form of {{l|nn|stare}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{nn-noun-m1}}\n\n# {{nn-former|stær|2012}}\n\n{{C|nn|Birds}}\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Verb===\n{{pt-verb|pres=stou|pret=stive|part=stado}}\n\n# {{obsolete spelling of|pt|estar}}\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{rfinfl|pt}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:pt:Priberam}}\n\n==Romanian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|ro|en|star}}. {{doublet|ro|aster|stea}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{ro-noun|n|staruri}}\n\n# {{l|en|star}} {{gl|famous person}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{ro-noun-n-uri}}\n\n==Sabir==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|pml|it|stare||to be}}.\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|pml|verb}}\n\n# to [[be]]\n\n===References===\n* Feissat et Demonchy, ''Dictionnaire de la Langue Franque, ou Petit Mauresque''\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|sh|ine-pro|*steh₂-}}{{dercat|sh|ine-bsl-pro|ine-pro|inh=2}}\n{{inh+|sh|sla-pro|*starъ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sh-IPA|stȁr}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{sh-adj|stȁr|def=stȃrī|comp=stàrijī}}\n\n# [[old]]\n#: {{ant|sh|mlȃd}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sh-adj-full|star|o|starij|e}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|sh|prastar}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:sh:HJP|d1tnXhE%3D}}\n* {{R:sh:HJP|d1tnXhA%3D}}\n\n==Slovene==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{root|sl|ine-pro|*steh₂-}}{{dercat|sl|ine-bsl-pro|ine-pro|inh=2}}\n{{inh+|sl|sla-pro|*starъ}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{sl-IPA|stȁr}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{sl-adj|stȁr|starȇjši}}\n\n# [[old]], [[aged]]\n#: {{ant|sl|mlad}}\n#: {{uxi|sl|'''Star''' sem dvajset let.|I'm twenty years '''old'''.}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{sl-decl-adj|stàr}}\n{{rfinfl|sl|adjective}}<!-- also stàr, stára, staró -->\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|sl|prestàr}}\n\n===Further reading===\n{{R:sl:FR}}\n\n==Venetan==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|vec|la|stō|stāre}}. Compare {{cog|it|stare}}.\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|vec|verb}}\n\n# {{lb|vec|transitive}} to [[stay]] or [[remain]]\n# {{lb|vec|transitive}} to [[live]] (somewhere)\n\n====Conjugation====\n{{vec-conj-auto}}"}}